>Adam, you have advocated VC++ on several occasions. I have used both VC++ 
>and Unix based tools, and I am very curious why you think that VC++ is better.
>Would you please list in what aspects the Unix [say GNU] tools are inferiour
>to VC++? [Except for lacking a fast UI building mechanism, I agree on this one]

It's really pretty simple.  First, there's plenty of easily accessed 
on-line help.  I put the cursor on my code where it says printf, InitInstance,
you-name-it, hit F1, and there is my help.  I don't switch to a command prompt
to use man pages or other help system.

Second, there is simple easy to use make utility.  I select my source files,
object files, libraries, resources, etc.  from a nice file listing.  It 
scans the files for dependencies and everything is taken care of.  I press
Build, and it compiles and links my file.

Third, what are compiler switches?  I don't have to know a single compiler
switch as they are all categorized and displayed in plain english in a 
dialog, along with lots of stuff I've never looked at, and might never need
to look at.  Want to switch to a debug build, takes 5 keystrokes.

Fourth, the debugger.  People have said that VC++'s debugger is terrible,
I don't have the experience with other debuggers to really say.  I can say
I find the debugger powerful and easy to use.  In unix, we were told we 
could use something called dbx(?).  I found printf's to be easier than 
trying to learn some arcane thing like that.  I originally did the same
when I got VC++.  Now, instead of using a printf to check a variable, object
state, etc., I mark a break in my code right there were I type and edit it,
and run the debugger.  When the program gets there, I bring up a browser,
enter the name of the variable, this, whatever and I see everything about
it.  Pointers are double-clicked and their contents are shown too.  

I don't every leave my editor to do anything.  Everything is there and it
is easy to learn and use, and it's easy to get things done.
My complaints:  I can only open 20 files.  And (though I've not needed yet)
the maker can't manage multiple targets in a single project.  This, I think,
is corrected in the next version, I hope.  

I also like and use the Wizards.  These are really only useful if you are
writing a windows based app, but can make things very easy in some cases.
I also use the resource editor for things like dialogs and bitmaps, but I've
never done it without them, so I don't know what it's like if I don't have
them.

Oh, and I guess if we were to compare with a unix environment, we would 
have to compare emacs or vi to the editor you get with VC++.  Frankly, I 
think vi and emacs suck, and all the power in the world won't ever win in
my book over the plain and simple editor you get with VC++ or even 
windows notepad.  I had a class last fall, and used emacs alot, and got
fairly proficient in it.  I could actually search, copy/paste, and even
copy/paste more than a screen's full of text from one file to another.
I even got a nice shell with an infinite scroll-back, and know dozens
of alt-, control-, and meta-key sequences.  Most just to do the simple 
things I could figure out in 5 seconds in notpad, NeXT edit.  A semester 
later, I have forgotten it all, and when I sit down and try to remember it
to get something done fast, I get pissed because it's not going to happen
fast, becasue I have to relearn all sorts of stupid little things.  It's
just not worth the trouble.  Hey, I know lisp (scheme, actually) pretty 
well, so I could do lots of cool stuff in emacs, right?  Give me a break,
people talk about how MS loads up their software with all sorts of useless
bells and whistles.  I am using vi right now.  Just recently I 
learned how to delete a character from the middle of a row, but I still
cannot delete the LF to merge two lines.  Oh well.  I don't care to learn
something that is that stupid, and shouldn't have to be learned.  I still
screw up alot and go down a line instead of left.  This shit is seriously
in the dark ages.  Every time I see someone post a search string to solve
someones problems, I just have to laugh.

Basically, I don't want anyone to tell me that there is XXX help system,
and there is XXX cool editor with all these fancy features, and there is
also this cool infinitly-expandable make, and that gcc is cross-platform,
etc, etc.  Ten thousand powerful, free unix apps and tools don't mean 
that much when there is something that does the exact same things almost
all the time, and is a thousand times simpler to use and learn.

I'm ranting pretty bad at this point, but I hope I anwered your question.

Adam Hayek


