u1376@sparc10.cs.uiuc.edu (hayek adam michael) writes:
>Fourth, the debugger.  People have said that VC++'s debugger is terrible,
>I don't have the experience with other debuggers to really say.  I can say
>I find the debugger powerful and easy to use.

Until you've used other debuggers you can't hardly call it powerful.

VC++'s debugger is a piece of junk.  Take it from me, I've been
helping to build really powerful debuggers for nearly five years now.

While VC++'s debugger does have basic functionality, that
functionality is hidden within modal dialogs that make it extremely
difficult to use.  When debugging a complicated application it takes
forever to get any real information out of it due to the poorness of
its data display functionality.

I hear VC++ 2.0 improves debugger interaction greatly.  It better --
the current product simply sucks for anything the least bit
complicated.

>In unix, we were told we 
>could use something called dbx(?).  I found printf's to be easier than 
>trying to learn some arcane thing like that.

I could see how it would be hard to remember the basic commands:

	run
	stop in function_name
	stop at line_number
	list
	list file_name
	step
	next
	print <expression>
	quit

Damn, that's difficult.

You probably didn't have documentation on it beyond a man page, which
I admit isn't really appropriate, but it's not a complicated piece of
software.

Even so, dbx isn't a modern UNIX debugger.  I believe you'd be right
at home using SparcWorks, Softbench, or my own company's ObjectCenter.
Back when dbx was written GUIs were research material.

>I don't every leave my editor to do anything.  Everything is there and it
>is easy to learn and use, and it's easy to get things done.

And the editor has no parenthesis balancing, automatic formatting, or
way to move around without removing your fingers from the home-row.
It's usable, but if you're writing a lot of code use something else.

>And (though I've not needed yet)
>the maker can't manage multiple targets in a single project.  This, I think,
>is corrected in the next version, I hope.  

Me too.  I can't tell you how annoying it was to build a set of
interacting applications that shared a common DLL.  I had as many as
five instances of VC++ running at once because the @#^@#% thing didn't
understand multiple make targets.  It was great for a single target,
but sucked if you had to do anything more complicated.  Real products
are rarely single-target!

>Oh, and I guess if we were to compare with a unix environment, we would 
>have to compare emacs or vi to the editor you get with VC++.  Frankly, I 
>think vi and emacs suck, and all the power in the world won't ever win in
>my book over the plain and simple editor you get with VC++ or even 
>windows notepad.

I'm not impressed with vi either, but emacs has so many features that
make it easier to write C code that it's worth learning.  The
automatic indention and brace balancing alone are worth the price of
admission.

>I am using vi right now.  Just recently I 
>learned how to delete a character from the middle of a row, but I still
>cannot delete the LF to merge two lines.  Oh well.

"J" for "join".  A capital-J, of course.

>This shit is seriously in the dark ages.

Considering that vi predates Microsoft, that's pretty much true.  Vi
is based on a line editor (like edlin, only much more powerful) and
retains much of that flavor.  Emacs is even older -- it dates back to
at least the early 70's.

Emacs 19, the newest version, has a point-and-click interface that is
rather similar to every other simple GUI-based editor.  You'd be right
at home.

We could argue until we're blue in the face over which tools are
better, but your experience with UNIX tools appears limited to the
very basic tools provided free with most systems.  The commercial
tools are considerably more advanced and correct most of the
deficiencies you believe UNIX tools have (with the possible exception
of a good Makefile generator, which I've never run into in any
product).

Happy hacking,

jim frost
